Below is a clean, step-by-step guide to enable GPU support for PyTorch in your Python 3.10 virtual environment. Follow carefully to replace your current CPU-only install (2.10.0+cpu) with CUDA support.

✅ 1. Verify GPU and CUDA compatibility

Before installing anything, confirm your system actually supports CUDA:

nvidia-smi

If this command works and shows your GPU, you’re good. If not, install/update your NVIDIA drivers first. PyTorch wheels already bundle CUDA runtime, so you usually do NOT need full CUDA Toolkit, only proper drivers.

✅ 2. Activate your virtual environment

Enter your project environment:

# Windows
venv\Scripts\activate

# Linux / macOS
source venv/bin/activate

You already mentioned entering venv — just make sure it is active before continuing.

✅ 3. Upgrade pip (important)
python -m pip install --upgrade pip

This prevents many wheel compatibility issues.

✅ 4. Remove CPU-only PyTorch (critical step)

Because you currently have:

import torch
torch.__version__
# '2.10.0+cpu'

You must uninstall it first:

pip uninstall -y torch torchvision torchaudio

Do not skip this — mixing builds causes GPU to fail.

✅ 5. Install CUDA-enabled PyTorch

Install the CUDA 12.8 build (as you intended):

pip install torch torchvision --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu128

This wheel already includes CUDA runtime.

✅ 6. Install project dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

If your requirements file contains torch, make sure it does not reinstall the CPU version. If it does, remove that line.

✅ 7. Install OpenCV
python -m pip install opencv-python

(Using python -m pip avoids path confusion.)

✅ 8. Verify GPU is working

Run this in Python:

import torch

print("Torch version:", torch.__version__)
print("CUDA available:", torch.cuda.is_available())
print("GPU name:", torch.cuda.get_device_name(0) if torch.cuda.is_available() else "No GPU")

✅ Expected output:

version should show +cu128

CUDA available: True

your GPU name printed

🔧 If CUDA shows False

Check these common issues:

NVIDIA driver too old

Installed inside wrong venv

CPU torch got reinstalled by requirements

Running inside WSL without GPU support

Laptop running on integrated graphics only

🧠 Quick sanity test

Try a tensor on GPU:

x = torch.rand(3,3).cuda()
print(x.device)

Expected:

cuda:0
🚀 You’re done

Once torch.cuda.is_available() returns True, your GPU acceleration is fully enabled and PyTorch will automatically use CUDA when tensors/models are moved to the GPU.


🚀 Step 5 — Install CUDA-enabled PyTorch

You chose CUDA 12.8 wheels. Install with:

pip install torch torchvision --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu128
What this does

Downloads GPU-enabled PyTorch

Includes CUDA runtime internally

No separate CUDA install needed

Works with modern NVIDIA drivers

After install, version should look like:

2.10.0+cu128

(not +cpu)

📦 Step 6 — Install your project requirements

Now install other dependencies:

pip install -r requirements.txt

⚠️ Important check:

Open requirements.txt and make sure it does NOT contain:

torch
torch==...

If it does, it may reinstall the CPU build and break GPU support.

🎥 Step 7 — Install OpenCV

You already planned:

python -m pip install opencv-python

Using python -m pip ensures the package goes into the active venv.

✅ Step 8 — Verify CUDA is working

Run Python:

import torch

print("Torch version:", torch.__version__)
print("CUDA available:", torch.cuda.is_available())

if torch.cuda.is_available():
    print("GPU:", torch.cuda.get_device_name(0))
✅ Correct output should show

version contains +cu128

CUDA available: True

Your GPU name appears

🧠 Step 9 — Quick GPU test

Final sanity check:

x = torch.rand(3, 3).cuda()
print(x.device)

Expected:

cuda:0

If you see this, GPU acceleration is fully working.

🚨 Common problems (and fixes)

Problem: CUDA available = False

Usually caused by:

❌ NVIDIA driver too old

❌ Installed outside venv

❌ CPU torch reinstalled by requirements

❌ Using AMD GPU (not supported by CUDA)

❌ Running inside unsupported WSL setup

🏁 Summary

You started with:

PyTorch CPU-only

After these steps you should have:

CUDA-enabled PyTorch

GPU visible to torch

Faster model training

Proper virtual environment setup

To enable GPU support in PyTorch, you need to replace your current CPU-only installation with a CUDA-enabled build and make sure your system can actually use the GPU. Right now your environment shows torch.__version__ == '2.10.0+cpu', which means PyTorch is running entirely on the processor. The goal of the following steps is to install a version compiled with CUDA so PyTorch can offload heavy tensor operations to your NVIDIA GPU.

First, confirm that your machine has a compatible NVIDIA GPU and proper drivers. Open a terminal and run nvidia-smi. If the command displays your GPU name, driver version, and memory usage, your system is ready. If the command is not recognized or fails, install or update your NVIDIA drivers before continuing. You typically do not need the full CUDA Toolkit because the official PyTorch wheels already bundle the required CUDA runtime; the driver is what matters most.

Next, activate your Python 3.10 virtual environment. This ensures all packages install into the correct isolated environment instead of your global Python. On Windows, run venv\Scripts\activate. On Linux or macOS, run source venv/bin/activate. Once the environment is active, upgrade pip using python -m pip install --upgrade pip. Keeping pip updated avoids many wheel compatibility and dependency resolution issues.

Because you currently have the CPU build of PyTorch, you must remove it before installing the GPU version. Run pip uninstall -y torch torchvision torchaudio. This step is critical—mixing CPU and CUDA builds often results in torch.cuda.is_available() returning False even when a GPU is present.

After cleanup, install the CUDA-enabled build of PyTorch. Using your chosen CUDA 12.8 wheels, run pip install torch torchvision --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu128. This downloads binaries that already include the CUDA runtime. When the installation finishes, your torch version string should contain +cu128 instead of +cpu.